               <p>Do you know the last witness 
               <persName id="t17850914-185-person1679">
                  John
                   Hart
               <interp inst="t17850914-185-person1679" type="surname" value="Hart"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17850914-185-person1679" type="given" value="John"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17850914-185-person1679" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            ? - I know him now.</p>
               <p>Do you remember any conversation between Hart and you? - I remember him, telling the words to the man just behind me, that he has just told you, about the prisoner being the man that stole the coach and horses.</p>
               <p>Did Hart ever tell you and Rowley to swear plump against him, or he would not be fully committed? - No, Sir.</p>
               <p>Nor anything to that purpose? - Nothing to that purpose.</p>
               <p>Did anybody tell you so at that time? - No, Sir, nobody.</p>
               <p>PRISONER's DEFENCE.</p>
               <p>What I said is certainly true, concerning what them people said, but when Mrs. Gosling found her son was cast to be transported, she has owed me ill-will ever since; and she would not come herself, nor get Mrs. Newmarsh, but she said, I must subpoena her, she said her son was transported on my account; I have nobody belonging to me, but a poor mother, and she is obliged to work for her bread, I have nobody to my character; I get my bread either by the silk business or weaving, I hope you will take it into consideration, I am young with child, and I never was guilty of any such thing before.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t17850914-185-verdict849" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t17850914-185-verdict849" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>Court to Prisoner. The perjured defences set up on behalf of prisoners, has long been the disgrace of the criminal courts of this country; I have thought it my duty, ever since I have sat in a criminal court of justice, to pay great attention to that circumstance, and to do all that lay in my power to prevent the continuance of so wicked and so dangerous a practice; for the mischief of such perjured defences by no means terminates in an unjust-acquittal, if believed; for that, though a failure of justice, and consequently a great mischief, is but a very small one to the mischief that follows from the frequency of this kind of perjuries, because they induce a court and jury to look with a suspicious eye on the defences of prisoners even when true; they require to be more strongly proved than any other kind of defence, in order to gain credit with the jury, so that the innocent may as often be hurt as the guilty: this is therefore the worst of all offences, except that most horrid of all offences, of which it falls very little short, the crime of murder; and no perjury can be more mischievous than that which frequently occurs in the defence of prisoners. I have therefore made it a point, where there appears strong and cogent grounds before the court on the trial of prisoners, to induce them to suspect, or rather to believe, that a witness is perjured, to put the matter into a way of trial, and to pursue to justice and condign punishment the offenders, if on a full and impartial hearing of a second jury they should be found guilty; and it appears to me that no trial can afford the party accused a better chance of justification, because, before a party can be found guilty, there must be the concurrent testimony of two juries; therefore, it would be idle and nugatory in me, and in the court, to direct a prosecution of that sort, and where it was afterwards supported by clear and satisfactory evidence, to pass a slight sentence on the<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="178509140210"></xptr> offenders; for such sentence would be a mockery of justice: however, considering the situation of the prisoner, the court will remember at the same time a degree of mercy with justice, and will nor pass so severe a sentence as might be passed on this prisoner; supposing that the might be ignorant in some degree of the full enormity of her guilt; sentence, however, somewhat severe, it is the duty of the Court to pass, and it is the sentence of the Court, that you, 
